\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The topological matter has been studied extensively recently in different
 platform 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "laughlin1983anomalous,wang2009observation,hasan2010colloquium,qi2011topological,stuhl2015visualizing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 One of the interesting feature is that the topological matter is protected
 by topology against local perturbations, such as, the quantization of Hall
 conduct is robust under impurity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "von1986quantized,nagaosa2010anomalous,stormer1999fractional"
literal "false"

\end_inset

; another unique character of the topology matter is the appearance of the
 edge state at the boundary of the sample 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jackiw1976solitons,su1979solitons"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The bulk topological invariants and the number of the edge states can be
 connected by the bulk-edge correspondence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wen1992theory,hasan2010colloquium"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Though the equilibrium properties have been widely explored, the non-equilibrium
 dynamics of topological system is still under investigation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "heyl2018dynamical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

(Dynamical quantum phase transition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "heyl2017dynamical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Dynamical chern number, linking number 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "PhysRevLett.118.185701,flaschner2018observation,tarnowski2019measuring"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The quench process is the typical non-equilibrium process which have been
 studied in different topological systems.
 On one hand, the bulk topological invariants, such as Chern number, is
 known to be unchanged under unitary dynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "d2015dynamical,caio2015quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and they are unchanged during the quench processes.
 However, the non-unitary processes, such as the dissipation or decoherence
 process, will change the bulk topological invariants during quench process
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "aidelsburger2011experimental,aidelsburger2013realization,atala2014observation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since the bulk-edge correspondence is only valid for the equilibrium situation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "d2015dynamical,caio2015quantum,wilson2016remnant,hu2016dynamical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the dynamics of the edge states in the boundary of the topological system
 is still elusive 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wang2019experimental,yi2019observing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, for example, Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "caio2015quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 studies quenches between topological and non-topological phases in Haldane
 model, while observing presence or absence of edge modes; Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hu2016dynamical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To investigate the dynamics of the edge states have attracted a lot of
 attention 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "d2015dynamical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In addition, how to experimentally observe the dynamics of the edge state
 is still an open question.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantum walk (QW), which can be used to construct universal quantum
 computation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "childs2009universal,childs2013universal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, has been shown to be a powerful platform to study the equilibrium and
 non-equilibrium topological properties of spin-orbital systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "PhysRevA.82.033429,Kitagawa2012,asboth2012symmetries,asboth2013bulk,asboth2014chiral,obuse2015unveiling,barkhofen2017measuring,cardano2016statistical,flurin2017observing,mochizuki2016explicit,xiao2017observation,schreiber2010photons,crespi2013anderson"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Particularly, it has been used to observe the bound states 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kitagawa2012observation,chen2018observation,nitsche2019eigenvalue"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Different QWs have been experimentally realized in different experiment
 platform, such as photonics
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kitagawa2012observation,schreiber2010photons,broome2010discrete,chen2018observation,xu2018measuringd,xu2018measuringw"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, neutral atoms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "karski2009quantum,mugel2016topological"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, superconductor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "flurin2017observing,yan2019strongly"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and trapped ion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "xue2009quantum,zahringer2010realization"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trapped ions system, which can be accurately controlled and manipulated
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "leibfried2003quantum,blatt2012quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, is one of the most idea platform for investigating quantum information
 processing and no-equilibrium dynamics of many-body system 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "eisert2015quantum,zhang2017observationm,zhang2017observationt"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Particularly, QW has been realized in one or two trapped 
\begin_inset Formula $^{40}\text{Ca}^{+}$
\end_inset

 ions by the phase space operation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "xue2009quantum,zahringer2010realization"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Here, we proposed to encode QW on the Fock space of the phonon, which is
 similar to the Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "oka2005breakdown"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the zero-number phonon state (the vacuum state) acts as the natural
 boundary of the QW.
 With carefully designed the laser sequences, the dynamics of the edge state
 can be experimentally investigated.
 We carefully analyze the quench dynamics of the edge state by tuning different
 parameters in this system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
THEORETICAL BACKGROUND
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One dimensional discrete QW is quantum version of the classical random walk.
 The walker is described by two internal states (denoted by
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\right\rangle ,\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and the position state (labeled as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

), and the internal state and the position state can be coupled through
 the coin operation 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta,x)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the control parameter and it may dependent on the position of the walker
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
 We focus on the split-step quantum walk (SSQW) and its one-step floquet
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2}) & = & S_{+}R(\theta_{2})S_{-}R(\theta_{1})\label{eq:1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum|i\pm1\rangle\langle i|\otimes|\uparrow\rangle\left\langle \uparrow\left|+1\otimes\right|\downarrow\right\rangle \langle\downarrow|$
\end_inset

 and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta)=\sum_{i}|i\rangle\langle i|\otimes\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}\sigma_{y}\theta/2}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 (the coin operator is independent of the position 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
 The quantum state of the SSQW can be obtained by: 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Psi\rangle_{n}=U^{n}(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})|\Psi\rangle_{0}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Psi\rangle_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the initial state of the evolution (generally, we begin the evolution
 of the system with a product state).
 The effective Hamiltonian of this periodical system can be derived from
 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})=e^{-iH_{\mathrm{eff}}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{eff}}=\int_{k}E(k)n(k)\cdot\sigma\otimes|k\rangle\langle k|$
\end_inset

 in momentum space, where the dispersion relation and Bloch vector:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\cos E(k) & =\cos\left(\theta_{2}/2\right)\cos\left(\theta_{1}/2\right)\cos k-\sin\left(\theta_{1}/2\right)\sin\left(\theta_{2}/2\right)\nonumber \\
n_{x}(k)= & \frac{\cos\left(\theta_{2}/2\right)\sin\left(\theta_{1}/2\right)\sin k}{\sin E(k)}\nonumber \\
n_{y}(k)= & \frac{\sin\left(\theta_{2}/2\right)\cos\left(\theta_{1}/2\right)+\cos\left(\theta_{2}/2\right)\sin\left(\theta_{1}/2\right)\cos k}{\sin E(k)}\nonumber \\
n_{z}(k)= & -\frac{\cos\left(\theta_{2}/2\right)\cos\left(\theta_{1}/2\right)\sin k}{\sin E(k)},
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=(\sigma_{x},\sigma_{y},\sigma_{z})$
\end_inset

.
 To determine the phase diagram of the QW, two different time frames which
 are defined by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U_{1}(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})=R\left(\theta_{1}/2\right)S_{+}R\left(\theta_{2}\right)S_{-}R\left(\theta_{1}/2\right),\nonumber \\
U_{2}(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})=R\left(\theta_{2}/2\right)S_{-}R(\theta_{1})S_{+}R\left(\theta_{2}/2\right).\label{eq:2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

should be considered.
 These two time frames have chiral symmetry and the whole phase diagram
 can be described by a pair of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}\times\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

 topological invariants 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "asboth2013bulk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\nu_{0}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}(\nu^{\prime}+\nu^{\prime\prime}),\nonumber \\
\nu_{\pi}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}(\nu^{\prime}-\nu^{\prime\prime}),\label{eq:3}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is the winding of the eigen-state in the first time frame and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 is the winding in the second time frame (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 1
width ""
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figure/fig_1.svg
	width 17.5cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:1"

\end_inset

 Split-step quantum walk with the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}=\frac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 a shows the dispersion relationship which is independent of the time frame;
 the blue and red dash lines represent the cases which the energy gap close
 at the quasi-energy 0 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

and character the phase transition points.
 b and c correspond to the two time frames with chiral symmetry to obtain
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}\times\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

 topological invariants.
 In the cases, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{\prime}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{\prime\prime}=0$
\end_inset

 thus based on Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\pi}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the topological character of the different phases in the QW, when
 crossing one phase to another topological phase in the real space, there
 is a bound state appear at the boundary of these two phases.
 In one dimensional QW, the bound state can be formed with inhomogeneous
 rotations in space between distinct regions and it has been observed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kitagawa2012observation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The different topological invariants in the two phases guarantee the robust
 of the bound state.
 Especially, the vacuum can be viewed as a special phase and the bound state
 can appear at the boundary of a semi-finite QW system (see Sup.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:A"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for a simple model with analytical eigen-state results).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to investigate the dynamics of the bound state between the quench
 of the system, we first evolved the system with initial effective hamiltonian
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{eff}}(\theta_{1}^{i},\theta_{2}^{i})$
\end_inset

 to form a stable bound state at the boundary.
 Then, suddenly (or slowly) changing the effective Hamiltonian of the system
 to the final Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{eff}}(\theta_{1}^{f},\theta_{2}^{f})$
\end_inset

 (or slowly change the parameter 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $(\theta_{1}^{i},\theta_{2}^{i})$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta_{1}^{f},\theta_{2}^{f})$
\end_inset

 along some path
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 ) and observe the dynamics of the bound state.
 The dynamics is strongly dependent of the quench parameter and the local
 manipulation of the boundary site.
 
\color red
Is it possible to change the bond state by local operator?->twisted boundary
 condition, the boundary of the material define the bulk topology.
\end_layout

