\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:2"

\end_inset

 a.
 Pulse sequences to realize QW with boundary.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow,n\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow,n\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 represent for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle \otimes\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle \otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|F=1,m_{F}=0\right\rangle \coloneqq\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|F=0,m_{F}=1\right\rangle \coloneqq\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}S_{1/2}$
\end_inset

 manifold, 
\begin_inset Formula $|n\rangle$
\end_inset

 for the state of the phonon with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 phonon.
 Auxiliary level 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 works for temporal state shelving and it has no occupation after the whole
 operations.
 Six steps are required for 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 along the black arrow direction.
 Step one and four are rotation operations which mix spin and other steps
 are for spin-dependent shifting.
 Phonon number deduces one in step two while blocked at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow,0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and then flips to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow,0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 in step three so it simulates the spin flipping operation at boundary.
 Adiabatic processes in step two and five fix the problem of phonon shifting
 simultaneously, works as an adiabatically 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

flipping between upper and lower state.
 b.
 Eigen-energy of modulated Jaynes-Cummings model 
\begin_inset Formula $H(t)$
\end_inset

 in subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow,n\right\rangle \leftrightarrow\left|\uparrow,n+1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (in the unit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

).
 Rabi frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 equals to detuning 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, while total transition time sets to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{10}{\Omega}$
\end_inset

.
 The adiabatic condition is satisfied when the evolution is much slower
 the time scale set by the energy gap, then adiabatically transform state
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow,n\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow,n+1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 c.
 Bulk togological invariant is defined with boundary condition.
 With introducing virtual site at 
\begin_inset Formula $n=-1$
\end_inset

 lattice, we can define the boundary 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cut link
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{-1,0}$
\end_inset

 (thus vacuum) then bulk phase with different 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Trapped ion system have been proved as a powerful platform for quantum simulatio
n.
 Here, we propose a way to realize the QW with boundary by a single 
\begin_inset Formula $^{171}\text{Yb}^{+}$
\end_inset

 ion in a three-dimensional Harmonic trap.
 In this system, the two level internal state of the QW (we call spin) is
 encoded in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|F=1,m_{F}=0\right\rangle \coloneqq\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|F=0,m_{F}=1\right\rangle \coloneqq\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}S_{1/2}$
\end_inset

 hyperfine manifold of ion 
\begin_inset Formula $^{171}\text{Yb}^{+}$
\end_inset

 with splitting 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\text{Hpf}}=2\pi\times12.6\text{\text{GHz}}$
\end_inset

; and the lattice sites of the QW are encode in the number of the phonons
 where the zero phonon state provide the natural boundary of the QW.
 To realize the QW, we need to implement two different basic operators 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\pm}$
\end_inset

.
 The rotation operator 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta)$
\end_inset

 is easy to realize by manipulate the hyperfine state (
\begin_inset Formula $|\uparrow\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\downarrow\rangle$
\end_inset

) by microwave or by Stimulate-Raman-Process.
 To implement the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 in the phonon space needs more work and is a bit complicated, where the
 auxiliary Zeeman energy level 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|F=1,m_{F}=1\right\rangle \coloneqq\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 will introduced to provide temporary shelving states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally, the interaction between the internal state (
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

) and the phonons with frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\text{phon}}$
\end_inset

 can be induced by a pair of proper selected stimulated Raman beams with
 frequency
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\text{Raman1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\text{Raman2}}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 , and the interaction can be described by the effective two level Jaynes-Cummin
gs Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{JC}}=\frac{\Omega}{2}a\sigma_{+}e^{i\delta t}+\text{h.c.}$
\end_inset

 under the rotation wave approximation (RWA), where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the effective Rabi frequency, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\text{Raman1}}-\omega_{\text{Raman2}}=\omega_{\text{Hpf}}\pm\omega_{\text{phon}}+\delta$
\end_inset

 (red (blue) sideband corresponded 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

) and phonon frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\text{phon}}$
\end_inset

) , 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{+}=\sum_{n=0}\sqrt{n+1}\left|n+1\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $a=\sum_{n=1}\sqrt{n}\left|n-1\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|$
\end_inset

) is the creation (annihilation) operation of phonon, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{+}(\sigma_{-})$
\end_inset

 is the flipping operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \left\langle \uparrow\right|$
\end_inset

) of spin.
 With this integration, the number of the phonons can be manipulated: the
 red sideband beam gives the transition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle \otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \leftrightarrow\left|n-1\right\rangle \otimes\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with Rabi frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{n,n-1}=\sqrt{n}\Omega$
\end_inset

 and the blue sideband gives the transition of 
\begin_inset Formula $|n\rangle\otimes|\downarrow\rangle\leftrightarrow|n+1\rangle\otimes|\uparrow\rangle$
\end_inset

 with Rabi frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{n,n+1}=\sqrt{n+1}\Omega$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the state of the phonon with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 phonon.
 The controlled hopping between the state with different number of phonons
 is almost the same as the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 besides the Rabi frequency is dependent of the number of the phonon (lattice
 site of the QW) .
 The phonon number dependence introduces additional difficulty, as a result,
 to implement the hopping operators 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 homogeneously is the main obstacle to realize the QW in this system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Actually, the hopping operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 indeed can be realized by some adiabatic processes (called Stimulated Raman
 Adiabatic Passage (STIRAP) ) which has already been used to cool the motional
 state in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "king1998cooling,wunderlich2007robust"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and solve the imhomogenious hopping 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "um2016phonon"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 According to the adiabatic theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "simon1983holonomy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, when Hamiltonian of the system changes slowly enough 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wunderlich2007robust"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the system will keep on the same eigen-state of the Hamiltonian for all
 the time if its initial state is a eigen-state of the initial Hamiltonian.
 In our current experimental setup, we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(t)=\Omega\sin(\frac{\pi t}{\tau})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(t)=\delta\cos(\frac{\pi t}{\tau})$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the total operation time) in the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{\text{JC}}}$
\end_inset

 to construct the time dependent Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H(t)$
\end_inset

 in the adiabatic process.
 The initial state 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left|n\right\rangle \otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 lower eigen-state of the two-band Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H(0)$
\end_inset

, when the parameter satisfies the adiabatic condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\theta(t)}{dt}\ll\text{gap}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\tan(\theta(t))=\frac{\Omega(t)}{\delta(t)}$
\end_inset

 is the angle on the Bloch sphere during the evolution).
 The system will keep evolving along the lower band of 
\begin_inset Formula $H(t)$
\end_inset

 and stay at the corresponding eigen-state of 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The adiabatic process is not dependent on the number of the phonon if the
 order of the eigen-states is given, see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "fig:2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

b for eigen-energy with given parameters during the whole process.
 
\color red
Give a level graph of H(t) to show the connection of the corresponding eigen-sta
te
\color inherit
 In order to speed up adiabatic process, further methods to suppress the
 non-adiabatic excitation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "um2016phonon"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and to reshape the waveform for shortcut Raman passage has been proposed
 and realized in experiment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "du2016experimental"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, based on the STIRAP method, the key operators 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 for the QW can be realized in a trapped ion and the whole QW evolution
 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 can be realized by the following six steps.
 For convenience, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega=\omega_{\text{Raman1}}-\omega_{\text{Raman2}}$
\end_inset

 and Zeeman splitting under magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\text{Zm}}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Apply rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}(\theta_{1})$
\end_inset

 in the spin space (spanned 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

), which can be easily realized by two Raman laser with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega=\omega_{\text{Hpf}}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding evolution is 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}(\theta_{1})=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left|i\right\rangle \left\langle i\right|\otimes[\cos(\theta_{1}/2)(\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \left\langle \uparrow\right|+\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|)-\sin(\theta_{1}/2)(\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|-\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \left\langle \uparrow\right|)]$
\end_inset

 (
\color red

\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 determined by pulse duration, which can be controlled precisely
\color inherit
) which is independent of the number of the phonon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Apply STIRAP for first red sideband between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, the frequency of the two Raman laser are chosen as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega=\omega_{\text{Hpf}}+\omega_{\text{Zm}}-\omega_{\text{Phon}}+\delta(t)$
\end_inset

 and the evolution can be effectively written as 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{-}=\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|\otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|+-\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left|n-1\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|\otimes\left|a\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Notice 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle\otimes|\downarrow\rangle$
\end_inset

 could not be driven at this step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Apply 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}(\pi)$
\end_inset

 in the spin space as in step 1, the evolution is: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left|n\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|\otimes(\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \left\langle \uparrow\right|-\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|+\left|a\right\rangle \left\langle a\right|)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Apply 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}(\theta)$
\end_inset

 in the space spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as in the step 1 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega=\omega_{\text{Hpf}}+\omega_{\text{Zm}}$
\end_inset

, the evolution is: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left|n\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|\otimes[\cos(\theta_{2}/2)(\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|+\left|a\right\rangle \left\langle a\right|)-\sin(\theta_{2}/2)(\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \left\langle a\right|-\left|a\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|)]$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Apply STIRAP for the first red sideband between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega=\omega_{\text{Hpf}}+\omega_{\text{Zm}}+\omega_{\text{phon}}+\delta(t)$
\end_inset

, the effective evolution is: 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}=-\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left|n+1\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|\otimes\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Apply 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{y}(\pi)$
\end_inset

 in the space spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega=\omega_{\text{Hpf}}+\omega_{\text{Zm}}$
\end_inset

, the evolution is: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left|n\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|\otimes(-\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \left\langle a\right|+\left|a\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|+\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \left\langle \uparrow\right|)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

