caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

b, the solid curve gives the time frame 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}R(\theta_{2})S_{-}R(\theta_{1})$
\end_inset

 while dash curve gives 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta_{1}/2)S_{+}R(\theta_{2})S_{-}R(\theta_{1}/2)$
\end_inset

.
 The initial state is prepared (cooling) onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle \otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 We study two cases: 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 is fixed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/2$
\end_inset

 than scan 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 (cyan dash line in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

a) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 is fixed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/2$
\end_inset

 than scan 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 (blue dash line in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

a).
 Except the phase boundary between different regions, soliton will also
 appear inside one regime, which corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\pi/2$
\end_inset

 eigen-state.
 We could deduce several steps as following: when preparing the particle
 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle \otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 state with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}=\pi/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}=-\pi$
\end_inset

 (orange square in vacuum phase), the evolution of the system: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left|0\right\rangle \otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle  & \stackrel{1}{\rightarrow}\left|0\right\rangle \otimes-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(\left|\uparrow\right\rangle +\left|\downarrow\right\rangle )\stackrel{1}{\rightarrow}\left|0\right\rangle \otimes\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & \stackrel{2}{\rightarrow}\left|0\right\rangle \otimes\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(-\left|\uparrow\right\rangle +\left|\downarrow\right\rangle )\stackrel{2}{\rightarrow}\left|0\right\rangle \otimes-\left|\downarrow\right\rangle .
\end{align}

\end_inset

After two steps the particle returns to its initial state with an additional
 minus sign.
 So we know that only the 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\pi/2$
\end_inset

 eigen-state exists here, which explains the discontinuityly changing inside
 one phase.
 Similar analyses could also be done with red and purple stars.
 While in the non-trivial phase with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}=\pi/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}=\pi$
\end_inset

 (yellow square in 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

), the probability change continuously for only 
\begin_inset Formula $E=0$
\end_inset

 eigen-state exist here:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|0\right\rangle \otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \stackrel{1}{\rightarrow}\left|0\right\rangle \otimes\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(-\left|\uparrow\right\rangle +\left|\downarrow\right\rangle )\stackrel{1}{\rightarrow}\left|0\right\rangle \otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle .
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

