\begin_layout Section
CONCLUSION
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:6"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we discuss the proposal to realize QW in phonon space with
 carefully designed laser sequence.
 The boundary condition will determine parameters region for the vacuum.
 Bound state will appear under the non-trivial phase without the need of
 spatial-dependent coin operation.
 By this convenience, the system can be used to study the Unitary evolution
 of the bound state under different dynamical processes.
 The behaviors of bound state will not be influenced by the velocity when
 evolution between neighbor regions, two eigen-states region and vacuum.
 The bound will only preserve between single eigen-state regions and two
 eigen-states region.
 The result will be determined by velocity when considering the evolution
 between two solitons.
 The bound state will remain more when the evolution is more close to quench
 dynamics.
 When introducing disorder, slow non-adiabatic dynamics bound state also
 appear as increasing of disorder strength.
 We give reasonable explanation for the conclusion above.
 See more details in Sup.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 fewer steps result for real experiment; Sup.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:D"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 the potential to study high dimension QW in our proposal; Sup.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:E"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 change time frames and symmetry during evolution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\start_of_appendix
Simple semi-infinite QW
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:A"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the character of the bound state, we consider a simple semi-infini
te QW as the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}=S_{x}R(\theta)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $x=0,1,2,\cdots$
\end_inset

) , where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{x}$
\end_inset

 is site-dependent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
S_{\text{0 }} & =\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|\otimes\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \left\langle \uparrow\right|+e^{i\phi}\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|\otimes\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right| & ,\nonumber \\
S_{x>0} & =\sum_{i}\left|n-1\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|\otimes\left|\downarrow\right\rangle \left\langle \downarrow\right|+\left|n+1\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|\otimes\left|\uparrow\right\rangle \left\langle \uparrow\right|\label{eq:sup_1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and the coin operator 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta)$
\end_inset

 homogeneous.
 There may be an additional phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 accumulated at site 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to test that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 according to the requirement of the particle hole symmetry (PHS).
 The bulk of the QW shows non-trivial winding thus it is a topological non-trivi
al phase.
 When it interferes with the vacuum, the bound state will appear at the
 boundary (
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

) and the energy gap will only close at 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0(\pi)$
\end_inset

 with the eigen-enenergy with 
\begin_inset Formula $0(\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 The wave function can be solved analytically (
\begin_inset Formula $U_{x}\left|\psi\right\rangle =e^{-iE_{b}}\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kitagawa2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in this situation, for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left|\psi^{E=0}(i)\right\rangle  & =\frac{1}{\mathcal{N}}(-1)^{i}e^{-i/\lambda}\otimes\left(\begin{array}{c}
1-\sqrt{2}\\
1
\end{array}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi/2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=-\frac{1}{\log(\sqrt{2}-1)}$
\end_inset

 is the localization parameter and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 is the normalization parameter.
 It is clear that there exist an exponent decay bound state which is the
 eigen-state of system with eigen-energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E=0$
\end_inset

 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sup_1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
The particle is initially prepared on 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle\otimes|\downarrow\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 After 50 steps, a exponent decay state appears at the boundary.
 The fitting localization parameter is close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The bound state will not be the exactly same state as the eigen-state solved,
 because we do not prepare the particle onto the eigen-state and there will
 have possibility of leaking to the bulk.
 We could also take this model into our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cut link
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 discussion in the main text: the bulk SSQW with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}=\pi/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, and the boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
 With setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to a horizontal line in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

a right phase diagram, crossing two regions in the phase diagram: 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\theta_{1}\leq2\pi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E=0$
\end_inset

; and when 
\begin_inset Formula $-2\pi\leq\theta_{1}\leq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Same results of eigen-energy could also be derivated from the analytical
 solution above.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figure/sup_1.svg
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:sup_1"

\end_inset

The simulation result with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi/2$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}=\pi/2,\theta_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 ).
 The histogram shows the possibility distribution after 50 steps and the
 orange line is the analytical solution of eigen-state.
 Two subplots are the mean and variance of QW verse steps.
 QW with boundary still represents acceleration of the random walk which
 shows the quadratic increment of deviation.
\end_layout

