\color inherit
change to to the second time frame preserve CS:
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 And then 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
focus on break PHS in second plot of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sup_4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which can be easily break with the coin operation mentioned in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:6"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 CS can also be broken with four steps quantum walk suggested in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "asboth2013bulk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We can consider two methods to break PHS: 1) 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\text{break1}}=S_{+}R\left(\theta_{1},\chi\right)S_{-}R\left(\theta_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 2) 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\text{break2}}=S_{+}R\left(\theta_{1},\chi\right)S_{-}R\left(\theta_{2},\chi\right)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $R\left(\theta\right)=\sum_{i}|i\rangle\langle i|\otimes\mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i}\sigma_{y}\theta/2-\mathrm{i}\chi\sigma_{z}}$
\end_inset

).
 When setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}=\pi/4$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}=\pi/2$
\end_inset

.
 First 20 steps SSQW is used to build steady-state, then suddenly quenching
 to another time-frame or break the symmetries.
 The result shows the the time-frame 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 are very close with only slightly different effects on the stability of
 bound state.
 The second plot shows the behavior of bound state when inducing 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

 terms in the coin operations.
 Blue, orange curves shows the single 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

 terms and green, red curves shows inducing 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

 terms in both coin operations.
 It's natural to find that the smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 is, the less bound state will be affected.
 After changing time-frame and breaking symmetry, the bound state will reduce
 but still exist.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figure/sup_4.pdf
	scale 25

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:sup_4"

\end_inset

Dynamics under different time-frames and symmetries.
 First 20 steps is used to built steady-state, then in first plot quench
 to another time-frame, in the second plot quenchs to another QW break PHS.
 In the first plot, red one correponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})=S_{-}C(\theta_{2})S_{+}C(\theta_{1})$
\end_inset

, the green one correponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

, the orange one correponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 which preserve CS as mentioned above and the blue one correponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\theta_{2},\theta_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 In the second plot, purple one orreponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

, green (
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=\pi/4$
\end_inset

) and red (
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=\pi/2$
\end_inset

) one correponds to the first methods to break PHS, blue (
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=\pi/4$
\end_inset

) and orange (
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=\pi/2$
\end_inset

) one correponds to the second methods to break PHS.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

